<p><strong>An Additive Model of Information Integration.</strong>
Figure 1 (below) shows a flowchart for information integration.  It
starts with the two characteristics, on the left.  This pair of
characteristics is the physical stimulus.  When the characteristics
are perceived, they are then mentally converted to psychological
values (as indicated by the arrows).  The flowchart shows that this
convertion is done independently for the two characteristics; for
example, the model asserts that the psychological value for
"level-headed" is the same regardless of whether the other
characteristic is "good-natured" or "humorless".  Once these two
psychological values have been established, they are then integrated
or combined into a single psychological value (labelled "Integrated
Psych. Value" in Figure 1).  The <em>additive</em> version of this
model asserts that the integrated psychological value is obtained by
<em>adding</em> the two individual psychological values.  Other
versions of the model hypothesize <em>multiplication</em> of values,
or <em>averaging</em>, or more complicated processes.  We will be
investigating the additive model.  After the integrated psychological
value is determined, it is converted into an overt rating, i.e., the
response.

