<p><strong>Laboratory results.</strong> In a laboratory version of
this experiment (see "To learn more," below), the mean ratings were
very well fit by the additive model.  Other kinds of information
integration are better fit by other integration functions.  For
example, consider playing poker against two other players.  Suppose
you are told the strength of the other players' hands - weak, medium,
or strong - and you must rate how tough it is to win against them.  In
this situation, peoples' ratings are best fit by a multiplicative
model.


<p><strong>So what?</strong> How people integrate information to make
decisions is a crucial issue in a wide range of situations.
Manufacturers want to know how consumers integrate information about
various products to decide what brand to buy.  Retailers want to know
how people combine information about stores to decide where to shop.
Managers want to know how employees combine information to make
critical decisions on the job.  Lawyers want to know how jurists
combine information to decide guilt or innocence.  You can think of
many other situations where an understanding of information
integration in decision making could have huge consequences.

<p><strong>To learn more:</strong> This exercise is based on an
